==Administration==
Ambattur comes under the new Sriperumbudur parliamentary constituency. It was previously under the North Chennai parliamentary constituency and along with Villivakkam, it was the largest assembly constituency in India. The [[delimitation]] process of assembly constituencies has given Ambattur a new identity of its own. Constituency no : 8, Tamil Nadu.  Once a major panchayat, Ambattur was made a township in the 1960s and a selection grade municipality from April 1975. In May 1992, it was raised to special grade municipality.<ref>[http://municipality.tn.gov.in/Ambattur/about_municipality.html]</ref> It was a municipality till October 2011. It was divided into 52 wards. Ambattur Municipality includes [[Padi, Chennai|Padi]], [[Korattur]], [[Anna Nagar]] Western Extension, [[Mogappair]] and Ambattur Industrial Estate areas. Now it is a part of Chennai and has 15 wards.

Ambattur shall come under Chennai Corporation from 2011 as per a government G.O.<ref>[http://beta.thehindu.com/news/cities/Chennai/article72657.ece  The Hindu dt 30-12-2009]</ref> On 15 June 2011, the chief minister of Tamil Nadu submitted a memorandum to the prime minister of India to expand the city limits of Chennai by which the Ambattur Municipality would come under the new scheme.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-06-15/chennai/29661418_1_water-supply-local-bodies-underground-sewerage | work=The Times Of India | title=Jaya to go ahead with expansion of city limit | date=15 June 2011}}</ref>

==Demographics==
{{Historical populations|type=
|1971|45586
|1981|115901
